        <name>22.1.2.6 Eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a 3x3 matrix</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let \(\textbf{A}\) be the following matrix: \(\textbf{A} = {@A@}\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What are the eigenvalues of \(\textbf{A}\)? Input&amp;nbsp;your answer, as a set (e.g. &lt;code&gt;{7,3,5/4}&lt;/code&gt;), in
    the box below:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The eigenvalues of \(\textbf{A}\) are [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]&lt;/p&gt;
[[feedback:prt1]]
&lt;p&gt;Find any eigenvector of \(\textbf{A}\). Input your answer, using column vector notation, in the boxes below:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;An eigenvector of \(\textbf{A}\) is [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]&lt;/p&gt;
[[feedback:prt2]]</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;Our matrix \(\textbf{A}\) is given to be \(\textbf{A} = {@A@}\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The eigenvalues \(\lambda_i\) (\(i = 1,\ldots, n\)) of \(\textbf{A}\) are the roots of the characteristic polynomial \(\chi\,(\lambda)\), which is calculated below:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\[\begin{array}{rcl} \chi\,(\lambda) &amp;amp; = &amp;amp; \textrm{det}\,\left({{@A@} - \lambda\,{@ident(3)@}}\right)\\ &amp;amp; = &amp;amp; \textrm{det}\,\left({@A_m_l_I@}\right)\\ &amp;amp; = &amp;amp; \cdots\\ &amp;amp; = &amp;amp; {@charpol@}.\end{array}\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Upon factorisation and solution of the characteristic equation \({@charpol@} = 0\), we arrive at the set of eigenvalues of \(\textbf{A}\), which is {@ta1@}.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;From the set of eigenvalues, we select any one eigenvalue \(\lambda\). Finding the kernel of {@A_m_l_I@} (i.e. the set of things which, when {@A_m_l_I@} is applied to them, gives the zero vector as its result) gives us a basis in the \(\lambda\)-eigenspace.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Any eigenvector in the&amp;nbsp;\(\lambda\)-eigenspace (which, therefore, is an example of an eigenvector of \(\textbf{A}\)) may be found by taking some linear combination of the relevant basis vectors. Whichever vector \(\textbf{v}\) you have chosen in this way will, by definition, satisfy the eigenvalue equation:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\[\textbf{A}\,\textbf{v} = \lambda\,\textbf{v}.\]&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
